value.0: What would these remains tell you if they could speak?

Value.value: Judging from the size and design of the manacle, it was made for the ankle of a giant, suggesting that the Seven Sisters of Hoet were not heroes, but probably slaves who were captured by the Abasi. Legendary lore tells of a tribe of desert giants that once wandered the Ankh'remun but has since left the desert. The rust on the manacles means they have been submerged in water; perhaps this valley floods.
A manacle that has been used recently from the traces of dried blood. The Abasi use it to sacrifice women kidnapped from the Oasis to the basilisk.
A large rusty manacle that fits around the waist of a normal-sized human being.

The sand is soft due to being overturned frequently. The basilisk probably resides beneath the sand during the heat of day, in subterranean tunnels beneath the compact sand. A basilisk, once it has eaten a few times its body weight (from human sacrifices), has no appetite and will not eat, and probably allows the Asabi it might otherwise devour into its lair to avoid the wrath of invading Desert Riders.

The bones within the area are not merely humanoid; many are also thin, hollow, and oddly shaped, probably belonging to the reptilian asabi. Apparently, the basilisk feeds upon them, as well. The lower half of the pillars all seem smooth.
The basilisk's nesting area, made of soft sand, is littered with bones, beetle shells, spider legs and dung.
